Locator Strategies in Playwright : 
	
Playwright also able to interact with the DOM, it stands for Document Object Model.
DOM : What is viewable when you use Chrome DevTools
	1) Recommended built-in locators
	2) CSS selectors, XPATH, and legacy locators


page.getByRole()
page.getByText()
page.getByLabel()
page.getByPlaceholder()
page.getByAltText()
page.getByTitle()
page.getByTestID()

Note : 
	**** 	if we are interacting with or asserting against an element we need to use await syntax.		****

page.getByRole()
	await page.getByRole('button',{name:'Sign in' }).click();	-- We have role name button and we are clicking the button.

Page.getByText()
	await expext(page.getByText('Jane Doe')).toBeVisible();		-- The element within the DOM we want to interact with has text Jane Doe, we are expecting that element is visible.

page.getByLabel()
	await page.getByLabel('username').fill('email@test.com')	-- This typically useful for inputs within applications as labels are used for making websites more accessible.

page.getByPlaceholder()


page.getByTestID()
	await page.getByTestID('nav-sign-in').click()				-- This we are using testID to click 


CSS and matching text
	await page.locator('article:hastext("Playwright")').click(); 

Click a <button> that has either a "Login" or "Sign in" text
	await page.locator('button:has-text("Log in"), button:has-text("Sign in")').click();

Using XPath
	await page.locator('xpath=//button').click();

Assertions in Playwright: https://playwright.dev/docs/test-assertions

	1) Locator assertions:
		This type of assertion is special as this type of assertion fails it automatically retries untill it either passes or it reaches the timeout.
		Example:
			await expect(locator).toBeVisible()
			await expect(locator).toContainText()
			await expect(locator).toHaveCount()
			await expect(page).toHaveURL()


	2) Value assertions: 
		This type of assertion will be evaluated one time and either pass or fail.
		This doesn't have await in syntax.
		Example:
			expect(value).toBe()
			expect(value).toContain()
			expect(value).toEqual()
			expect(value).toBeTruthy()
			expect(value).toHaveLength()










